He had had men hanged, although he wasn't a member of the judiciary.

7
00:00:49,360 --> 00:00:52,240
他写了很多关于《圣经》的文章
And he'd written extensively on Scriptures,

8
00:00:52,240 --> 00:00:54,800
虽然他也不是牧师
although he was no cleric or priest.

9
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:58,400
他的棺材是由大法官
His coffin was carried by the Lord Chancellor,

10
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:01,280
两位公爵和三位伯爵抬到这的
two dukes and three earls.

11
00:01:01,280 --> 00:01:03,400
这个人就是伊萨克・牛顿
That man was Isaac Newton.

12
00:01:10,800 --> 00:01:12,840
能够下葬威斯敏斯特大教堂
To be buried in Westminster Abbey

13
00:01:12,840 --> 00:01:16,120
通常是国王和贵族才有的荣誉
was an honour usually reserved for kings and nobles,

14
00:01:16,120 --> 00:01:18,400
牛顿这样的平民是没有这样特权的
not commoners like Newton.

15
00:01:19,560 --> 00:01:21,880
但牛顿并不是个平凡的人
But Newton was no ordinary man.

16
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:27,280
这里写道
Even here, it's written,

17
00:01:27,280 --> 00:01:32,320
“众人因这样杰出的存在而欣喜”
"Mortals rejoice that there has existed such an ornament of the human race".

18
00:01:32,320 --> 00:01:35,600
牛顿是第一位自然哲学家
Now, Newton was the first natural philosopher,

19
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:37,600
用现在的话来说 就是科学家
or scientist, as we now call him,

20
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:39,280
而人们以这种方式纪念他
to be honoured in this way.

21
00:01:39,280 --> 00:01:41,680
但他一定不是最后一个
But he certainly wasn't the last.

22
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:44,520
这是詹姆斯・克拉克・麦克斯韦
And here is James Clerk Maxwell.

23
00:01:44,520 --> 00:01:47,320
这是迈克尔・法拉第
Here, Michael Faraday.

24
00:01:47,320 --> 00:01:50,240
这是保罗・狄拉克
And here, Paul Dirac.

25
00:01:50,240 --> 00:01:53,480
人们还将他描述电子运动的方程
With his equation describing the behaviour of the electron

26
00:01:53,480 --> 00:01:57,400
刻在了威斯敏斯特大教堂的地面上
inscribed into the stone on the floor of Westminster Abbey.

27
00:02:06,240 --> 00:02:08,000
英国以这种方式
It's perhaps no coincidence

28
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,360
纪念其杰出的科学家
that a country that honours its leading scientists in this way

29
00:02:11,360 --> 00:02:13,960
因此拥有数量众多的领路人和改革者
has produced far more than its fair share

30
00:02:13,960 --> 00:02:16,360
也就不奇怪了
of trailblazers and innovators.

31
00:02:17,640 --> 00:02:21,680
解码DNA 解释遗传的科学家们
Men and women who explained heredity by decoding DNA.

32
00:02:26,880 --> 00:02:30,720
为每项太空计划提供物理学基础的科学家们
Who provided the physics for every space programme ever conceived.

33
00:02:33,680 --> 00:02:37,320
利用万维网转变人类交流方式的科学家们
And transformed communication for ever with the World Wide Web.

34
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:46,520
这个系列里 我想考察
In this series, I want to explore Britain's pivotal role

35
00:02:46,520 --> 00:02:48,920
英国在创建现代科学中发挥的关键作用
in creating modern science.

36
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:53,400
发掘每一个为现代科学做出贡献的人物
Reveal the characters who have made science what it is today.

37
00:02:55,640 --> 00:02:57,960
揭示英国在过去的300年中
Show how Britain has used its scientific strength

38
00:02:57,960 --> 00:03:00,080
如何运用其科学优势
for over 300 years.

39
00:03:01,480 --> 00:03:05,480
探究英国科学路在何方
And explore what the future holds for British science.

40
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:41,720
英国科学家不断地
British scientists have made and continue to make,

41
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:44,800
做出重大科学发现
some of the great scientific discoveries.

42
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:49,520
但从历史的角度看
But of equal importance from a historical perspective,

43
00:03:49,520 --> 00:03:53,320
同等重要的是科学研究手段的发展
was the development of the means by which we do science.

44
00:03:53,320 --> 00:03:57,680
提出理论 实验论证
The idea that you build theories, you test them by experiment

45
00:03:57,680 --> 00:03:59,800
最后发表结果
and you publish the results.

46
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:02,360
这就是科学方法
This is known as the scientific method.

47
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:05,120
也是科学的基础
It is the bedrock of science.

48
00:04:05,120 --> 00:04:10,800
这是由英国科学家率先使用并不断完善的
And it was developed and first used, to a large extent, here in Britain.

49
00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:20,120
这里是英国皇家学会
This is The Royal Society.

50
00:04:20,120 --> 00:04:23,520
世界顶尖科学家的联盟
A fellowship of the world's most eminent scientists

51
00:04:23,520 --> 00:04:26,120
成立于1660年
that has existed since 1660.

52
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:39,880
其成员几乎包括所有科学史上的重要人物
Its members include virtually all of the great names in science.

53
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:42,680
从达尔文到法拉第
From Charles Darwin to Michael Faraday.

54
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:49,360
就是这些人的构想和研究
These are people whose ideas and investigations

55
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:52,600
改变了我们对自然界的理解
have transformed our understanding of the natural world.

56
00:04:57,240 --> 00:04:59,920
他们改变世界的行为
That they were able to perform such a transformation

57
00:04:59,920 --> 00:05:01,560
已足够引人注目
is remarkable enough.

58
00:05:01,560 --> 00:05:03,840
同样值得注意的是
But what's also remarkable

59
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:06,240
很多皇家学会成员
is that many of The Royal Society's members

60
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:08,400
都将他们的杰出成就
would've traced their towering achievements

61
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:11,000
归功到一个人的研究上
back to the work of one man.

62
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:12,920
艾萨克・牛顿爵士
Sir Isaac Newton.

63
00:05:15,360 --> 00:05:17,560
这是牛顿的死亡面具
This is Newton's death mask.

64
00:05:17,560 --> 00:05:20,240
他死后
It's a plaster cast of his face

65
00:05:20,240 --> 00:05:22,880
依照他面部做成的石膏模型
that would've been taken moments after he died.

66
00:05:22,880 --> 00:05:25,320
趁尸体还有未凉
And the technique was to make these masks

67
00:05:25,320 --> 00:05:28,360
人们做成这些面具
whilst the body was still warm.

68
00:05:28,360 --> 00:05:32,760
这东西看起来确实很可怕
And it's really quite an eerie thing to look at.

69
00:05:34,680 --> 00:05:37,280
如果你将牛顿看待成一位物理学家
When you think of Newton as a physicist,

70
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:41,800
那么就会认为牛顿就是一堆抽象理论的集合
you think of Newton as almost an abstract set of theories.

71
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:46,040
你知道 F = MA 力等于质量乘以加速度
You know, F = MA, force equals mass times acceleration.

72
00:05:46,040 --> 00:05:48,680
想起他的万有引力定律
You think of his universal law of gravitation.

73
00:05:48,680 --> 00:05:52,840
第一个普适的物理定律
That first universal, physical law that's still used to this day

74
00:05:52,840 --> 00:05:56,720
今天依然应用此项定律向太阳系边缘或之外发射宇宙飞船
to send spacecraft to the edge of the solar system and beyond.

75
00:05:56,720 --> 00:05:59,240
但看看这个
But when you look at this,

76
00:05:59,240 --> 00:06:01,480
你会发现一个不同的牛顿
you see a different Newton.

77
00:06:01,480 --> 00:06:04,120
仅仅是一个人
You see Newton, the man.

78
00:06:15,480 --> 00:06:18,720
牛顿并不是很容易相处
Newton certainly wasn't the easiest person to get along with.

79
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:21,800
他强势 不怀好意
He was obsessive, malicious

80
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:24,640
而且易怒
and prone to outbursts of rage.

81
00:06:25,840 --> 00:06:27,920
但他的工作方式
But there was something quite extraordinary

82
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:30,280
也有些不同寻常
about the way that he worked.

83
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:36,120
在人类依然信仰魔法的年代
In an age when people still believed in magic,

84
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:39,840
牛顿提出了革命性的理论框架
Newton devised a revolutionary theoretical framework

85
00:06:39,840 --> 00:06:43,440
人们可以以此准确地探索自然的本质
with which to accurately investigate the nature of the world.

86
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:52,240
1642年 牛顿出生在
Newton was born in 1642

87
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:55,160
处于过渡期的英格兰
into an England that was a country in transition.

88
00:06:55,160 --> 00:06:57,160
那年 英国内战正式爆发
That was the start of the English Civil War.

89
00:06:57,160 --> 00:06:59,960
那是个人们仍在到处搜寻女巫的国家
It was a country where they were still hunting for witches.

90
00:06:59,960 --> 00:07:03,240
但也是个科学 理性思考
But also, it was a country where science,

91
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:06,800
开始蓬勃发展的国家
where rational thought, where reason were beginning to flower.

92
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:10,120
当时 一个伟大的问题
Now, at the time, one of the great questions

93
00:07:10,120 --> 00:07:12,360
是关于光的本质
was about the nature of light.

94
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:16,840
当时人们已经知道 如果你用太阳光照射棱镜
It was known that if you take a prism and shine sunlight through it,

95
00:07:16,840 --> 00:07:20,080
棱镜则会将太阳光
then it splits that sunlight

96
00:07:20,080 --> 00:07:22,240
分散成彩虹的颜色
into all the colours of the rainbow.

97
00:07:22,240 --> 00:07:23,760
而问题就是为什么
The question was why.

98
00:07:23,760 --> 00:07:26,680
之前主流的科学观点
Now, the prevailing scientific view

99
00:07:26,680 --> 00:07:28,840
太阳光是完美的
was that sunlight must be perfect.

100
00:07:28,840 --> 00:07:32,280
这要一路追溯到亚里士多德和其他古希腊哲学家
This dated all the way back to Aristotle and the Ancient Greeks.

101
00:07:32,280 --> 00:07:34,560
来自上天的东西
How could something that comes from the heavens

102
00:07:34,560 --> 00:07:36,400
怎么可能不是完美的
be anything other than perfect?

103
00:07:41,680 --> 00:07:44,480
当时大部分人对此的解释
The common explanation for the appearance of the colours

104
00:07:44,480 --> 00:07:47,720
是棱镜带来了杂质
was that they were impurities added by the prism

105
00:07:47,720 --> 00:07:49,800
污染了纯净的白光
to the pure white light.

106
00:07:52,160 --> 00:07:54,040
牛顿则认为这些颜色
Newton thought that the colours

107
00:07:54,040 --> 00:07:56,600
原来就存在于白光中
were already present in the white sunlight.

108
00:07:58,680 --> 00:08:00,320
但牛顿的可贵之处在于
But what set Newton apart

109
00:08:00,320 --> 00:08:03,360
他设计了实验
was the fact that he devised and performed an experiment

110
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:06,200
并以此验证自己的假设
to test his hypothesis.

111
00:08:17,720 --> 00:08:19,680
这就是牛顿的天才设计
Then, and here's the genius,

112
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:23,880
他在彩虹中放置了一条细缝
he introduced a slit into that rainbow beam.

113
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:28,080
这样他就可以分离出单色光
And that allowed him to isolate a particular colour of light

114
00:08:28,080 --> 00:08:31,400
然后再将单色光照向第二个棱镜
and shine that into a second prism.

115
00:08:31,400 --> 00:08:37,360
接着他观察有色光在墙壁上的偏转
Then he looked for the deflection of the coloured light onto his wall.

116
00:08:37,360 --> 00:08:40,160
看 就在那
You can see that over there.

117
00:08:40,160 --> 00:08:42,960
我现在将红光换成绿光
Now, look what happens

118
00:08:42,960 --> 00:08:48,440
看看接下来会发生什么
when I move the red light across the slit, to the green light.

119
00:08:48,440 --> 00:08:53,320
你会发现 照射在棱镜上的绿光
On the wall, what you see is green light into the prism

120
00:08:53,320 --> 00:08:55,960
也就是发出的绿光
equals green light out.

121
00:08:55,960 --> 00:09:01,240
这意味着颜色本身是纯净的
Now, that implies that the colours themselves are pure.

122
00:09:01,240 --> 00:09:05,480
棱镜并没有添加或除去任何东西
The prism is not adding or subtracting anything.

123
00:09:05,480 --> 00:09:10,000
这表明实验验证了牛顿的假设是正确的
That means that Newton's hypothesis was shown to be correct.

124
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:11,800
有色光本身
The colours themselves

125
00:09:11,800 --> 00:09:14,240
就是光线的基本组成部分
are the basic building blocks of light.

126
00:09:14,240 --> 00:09:18,960
白光是由所有的有色光组合起来的
And white light is made up of all those individual colours.

127
00:09:18,960 --> 00:09:20,960
这太神奇了
That's genius.

128
00:09:33,480 --> 00:09:37,000
牛顿率先使用今天所谓的“科学方法”
Newton was one of the first to interrogate nature

129
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:41,440
探索自然
using the principles of what we now call the scientific method.

130
00:09:41,440 --> 00:09:43,880
换句话说 他观察世界
In other words, he observed the world,

131
00:09:43,880 --> 00:09:47,960
提出理论解释观察到的现象
came up with theories to explain what he saw,

132
00:09:47,960 --> 00:09:51,600
接着用实验验证这些理论十分正确
then tested them with experiments to see if he was right.

133
00:09:56,240 --> 00:09:57,960
这种方法的优势在于
The power of this approach

134
00:09:57,960 --> 00:10:01,340
它意图排除已先入为主的构想
is that it aims to remove preconceived ideas.

135
00:10:01,340 --> 00:10:04,780
这么做 我们就可以
And in doing so, deliver a more accurate description

136
00:10:04,780 --> 00:10:06,220
更加准确地描述自然界
of the natural world.

137
00:10:10,500 --> 00:10:14,740
但他虽然思考清晰 实验技巧娴熟
But for all his clarity of thought and experimental technique,

138
00:10:14,740 --> 00:10:18,180
但似乎没有意识到
Newton himself seems to have been strangely unaware

139
00:10:18,180 --> 00:10:20,020
自己工作的重要性
of the importance of his work.

140
00:10:24,900 --> 00:10:27,060
这本书十分珍贵
This is a priceless book.

141
00:10:27,060 --> 00:10:30,380
它是牛顿著作《自然哲学的数学原理》
It is the first handwritten manuscript

142
00:10:30,380 --> 00:10:33,620
的第一份手稿
of Newton's great masterpiece, the Principia.

143
00:10:33,620 --> 00:10:35,900
书里第一次
It's in here the first time

144
00:10:35,900 --> 00:10:39,500
描述了万有引力定律
that the universal law of gravitation is outlined.

145
00:10:39,500 --> 00:10:41,260
他提出的运动定律
It's also his laws of motion

146
00:10:41,260 --> 00:10:44,380
也解释了宇宙万物的运动
that say how objects move around in the universe.

147
00:10:46,020 --> 00:10:47,580
这几乎是你大一整年
It's pretty much everything you do

148
00:10:47,580 --> 00:10:50,300
要学的物理
in the first year of an undergraduate degree in physics.

149
00:10:50,300 --> 00:10:54,500
而这本书背后的故事也令人着迷
And the story behind the writing of this book is fascinating.

150
00:10:54,500 --> 00:10:56,580
它也揭露了牛顿的其他方面
It reveals a lot about Newton.

151
00:10:57,820 --> 00:11:00,660
天文学家埃德蒙多・哈雷曾说过
The astronomer Edmond Halley said,

152
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:03,700
是否存在一个外有引力定律
"Is it true that there's a universal law of gravity

153
00:11:03,700 --> 00:11:06,980
可以解释所有星球的可观测到的运行轨道
"that can explain the observed orbits of the planets?"

154
00:11:06,980 --> 00:11:10,260
牛顿说 我已经证明了 几年前就证明过了
Newton said, "Yeah, I've proved it. I proved it a couple of years ago."

155
00:11:10,260 --> 00:11:12,060
然后他开始找笔记
And he went to look for his notes,

156
00:11:12,060 --> 00:11:14,300
但他找不到
and the story is that he couldn't find them.

157
00:11:14,300 --> 00:11:17,740
接着他坐下来 开始重写这个证明过程
And so he just sat down and wrote the whole thing out again.

158
00:11:17,740 --> 00:11:24,340
和哈雷的对话引出了整部《自然哲学的数学原理》
And it's that conversation with Halley that led to the Principia.

159
00:11:24,340 --> 00:11:26,580
我们会惊奇地发现
So, it's interesting to speculate

160
00:11:26,580 --> 00:11:29,100
如果把这事交给牛顿处理
that if it had been left up to Newton,

161
00:11:29,100 --> 00:11:31,740
科学史上最伟大的著作
then maybe the greatest work in the history of science

162
00:11:31,740 --> 00:11:33,340
根本就不会发表了
wouldn't have been published at all.

163
00:11:34,900 --> 00:11:39,260
探索自然的乐趣对牛顿来说也已经足够了
The joy of exploring nature was enough for Newton.

164
00:11:39,260 --> 00:11:42,860
著述 与别人分享知识
And the act of writing it down and sharing his knowledge

165
00:11:42,860 --> 00:11:45,940
可能就是次要的了
with others was somehow secondary.

166
00:12:03,140 --> 00:12:06,500
牛顿本身也充满了矛盾
Newton was certainly a man of contradictions.

167
00:12:06,500 --> 00:12:10,700
他生活在17世界中叶
Given that he lived and worked in the middle of the 17th century.

168
00:12:11,900 --> 00:12:16,980
站在理性时代的开端
He stood at the cusp, at the dawn of the Age of Reason.

169
00:12:16,980 --> 00:12:22,300
毫无疑问 他处在两个世界中
And so, he was undoubtedly a man with feet in both worlds.

170
00:12:22,300 --> 00:12:24,460
神秘世界和科学世界
The mystical and the scientific.

171
00:12:24,460 --> 00:12:27,740
他是占星家 炼金术士
He was an astrologer, an alchemist,

172
00:12:27,740 --> 00:12:31,500
但他也明白
